## JavaScript — banking_api_server

### Module Pattern

CommonJS only (`require`/`module.exports`). Do **not** use ESM `import`/`export`.

```javascript
'use strict';

const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();
const oauthService = require('../services/oauthService');
const configStore = require('../services/configStore');

// ...

module.exports = router;
```

### Async Route Handlers

Always wrap Express routes in try/catch. Use `async/await`, not `.then()` chains:

```javascript
router.post('/transfer', authenticateToken, async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const { fromAccountId, toAccountId, amount } = req.body;

    // Input validation at boundary only
    if (!fromAccountId || !toAccountId || !amount) {
      return res.status(400).json({ error: 'missing_fields' });
    }

    const result = await bankingService.transfer({ fromAccountId, toAccountId, amount });
    res.json(result);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('[transfer] Error:', err.message);
    res.status(500).json({ error: 'transfer_failed', message: err.message });
  }
});
```

### Session / Backend-for-Frontend (BFF) Pattern

Tokens are stored **only** in `req.session` — never sent to the browser:

```javascript
// ✅ Store in session
req.session.oauthTokens = tokens;
req.session.user = userClaims;
req.session.oauthType = 'admin'; // or 'user'

// ✅ Read from session
const { oauthTokens, user } = req.session;

// ❌ Never
res.json({ access_token: tokens.access_token }); // don't expose tokens
```

### Input Validation

Validate at API boundaries (user input, external APIs). Do **not** add defensive validation for internal function calls.

```javascript
// Validate shape, existence, and types
const { username, password } = req.body;
if (!username || typeof username !== 'string' || username.length > 100) {
  return res.status(400).json({ error: 'invalid_username' });
}

// Sanitize before using in queries (no SQL here, but same principle for headers/logs)
const safeUsername = username.trim().toLowerCase();
```

### Correlation IDs

Every request handler should propagate correlation IDs:

```javascript
const correlationId = req.headers['x-correlation-id'] || crypto.randomUUID();
req.correlationId = correlationId;
res.setHeader('x-correlation-id', correlationId);
```

